{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17293"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17293"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9983"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55536"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a complaint of numbness and tingling in his right hand. One week ago he sustained a dislocation to his right elbow during a game of football. A closed reduction was performed and since then the numbness has been present. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals loss of sensation on the skin over the medial 1.5 digits on both the palmar and dorsal surfaces of his right hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Median","Ulnar"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sensory loss described in the stem is characteristic of an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. The ulnar nerve provides sensation to the medial 1.5 digits, which includes the little finger and half of the ring finger, on both the palmar and dorsal surfaces of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and provides sensation to the skin over the deltoid region, not the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the anterior compartment of the arm and provides sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm, not the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensation to the posterior aspect of the arm and forearm and the dorsal surface of the hand, but not the medial 1.5 digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensation to the palmar surface of the lateral 3.5 digits and the tips of these fingers on the dorsal side, not the medial 1.5 digits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ulnar nerve is responsible for sensation over the medial 1.5 digits on both the palmar and dorsal surfaces of the hand.","Injury to the ulnar nerve can result in sensory loss in its distribution area, which includes the little finger and half of the ring finger.","Understanding the sensory distribution of peripheral nerves is crucial for diagnosing nerve injuries."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55536"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T16:13:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T16:14:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9983"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emo